In article <1993Mar14.043418.2037@altair.selu.edu>, fcs$1655@altair.selu.edu writes:> 8In article <1993Mar14.000511.14875@csi.uottawa.ca>, cbbrowne@csi.uottawa.ca (Christopher Browne) writes:
>> In article <1993Mar13.165350.2027@altair.selu.edu> fcs$1655@altair.selu.edu writes:
>>>In article <16536@rand.org>, jim@rand.org (Jim Gillogly) writes:
>>>> Not long, as it happens.  The method is called "Vigenere", and it's easy
>>>> to decrypt.  If it's long enough, it can be decrypted automatically, and
>>>> even quite short ones can be decrypted by using standard methods.
>>  
>>>> No, that's long enough.  Running an index of coincidence on the thing shows
>>>> the period is 8 -- that's the first major peak -- meaning that there are
>>>> 120/8 = 15 full periods.  Plenty for a Vigenere.  Running my automatic
>>>> Vigenere/Beaufort/Variant Vigenere/Porta program on it suggests that the
>>>> key is "theqwiik" and gives pretty good text.  Trying it with key "thequick"
>>>> gives the correct plaintext:
>>>> 
>>>>     greatart hasawayo fevoking continua lcomment aryitisa bottomle sssource
>>>>     ofinspir ationtoo thersiha vemyblin dspotsin termsofu nderstan ding
>>>> 

>> 
>> It would be equivalent (if my permutation math is right) to using
>> the Vigenere system with some key of length 24 (24 = LCM(8,12)).  Take
>> the key "thequick," write it out 3 times, and then run it through
>> Vigenere using that 12 character key.  The result is (I think) the
>> key that would be used to decrypt the "doubly encrypted" message.
>> 
>> With the short message, and the correspondingly somewhat longer key
>> length, it could be more difficult to determine the key period.  But
>> it's probably still possible.
>> 
>> Check out the book "Cryptanalysis for Microcomputers," which presents
>> software in BASIC to break (among other things) the Vigenere system.
>> 
>> All of the "experts" around here will tell you that learning how
>> to BREAK ciphering systems is a necessary prelude to trying to
>> construct one that is secure.  I'm VERY distant from being an expert,
>> but would tend to agree.  At worst, knowing how to break some of 'em
>> will show you:
>> a) Some methods to avoid.  (Why reinvent a broken wheel?)
>> b) Some tests that your method will have to "pass"
>> c) How to use up even MORE CPU time :-).
>> -- 
>> Christopher Browne                |     PGP 2.0 key available
>> cbbrowne@csi.uottawa.ca           |======================================
